Introduction¶

In this project, we will analyse the TMBD movie dataset, provided within the course and cleaned from original data on Kaggle. The original dataset was created on 30 August 2016, and lastly updated on 28 September 2017.

Here is a short overview of the features:

  • id - the movie TMBD id
  • imdb_id - the movie IMDb id
  • popularity - metric built on characteristics such as number of votes and views for the day, number of users who marked the movie as a "favourite" or who added the movie to their "watchlist" for the day etc. (more details can be found in Popularity)
  • budget - the budget in US dollars
  • revenue - the revenue in US dollars
  • original_title - the movie title
  • cast - the list of the main performers
  • homepage - the movie web page
  • director - the movie director
  • tagline - a short text which serves to clarify a thought for, or is designed with a form of, dramatic effect (Wiki)
  • keywords - keywords associated with the movie
  • overview - a short description of the movie
  • runtime - the movie length in minutes
  • genres - the list of genres the movie belongs to
  • production_companies - the list of production companies
  • release_date - the movie release date
  • vote_count - the number of users that rated the movie
  • vote_average - the average rating of the movie
  • release_year - the movie release year
  • budget_adj - the budget in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time
  • revenue_adj - the revenue in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time

We will analyse the dataset to shed light on following questions:

  1. Is there correlation between budget and revenue?
  2. Which genres are associated with high revenues?
  3. What is the optimal movie runtime with respect to revenue?
  4. Are movies with high revenues rated highly by users?

Following features will be used to answer the questions:

  • budget_adj and revenue_adj - we will use adjusted values to compare movies released in different decades consistently
  • genres
  • vote_average - we will use this as a measure of movie popularity, it's basically user rating ranging from 0 to 10
  • runtime

We will keep id, original_title and release_year in order to identify the movies.

We will use descriptive statistics; inferential statistics or machine learning are not used to complete the project, and from this point of view, the findings are tentative and open to further exploration.

In [8]:
# Visualize the distributions of the numeric features to get a better picture
df.hist(figsize=(18,12));

Histograms support the observations above:

  • The number of movies released every year increases over time, which is expected. There are no obvious odd values.
  • The movie rating represented by feature vote_average follows a normal distribution - there are many average movies, some very bad movies with low rating below 3 and some very good movies with high rating above 8.
  • Most of the movies have popularity below 1. Since it is a little bit difficult to relate to this measure, i.e. it is not clear, what the normal values should be, we will not use this measure in the subsequent analysis.
  • The median runtime is 99 minutes - approximately one hour and forty minutes. However, there are also some extremely long movies.
  • Budget and revenue histograms are skewed to the right, which could be because many movies have zero, probably missing, budget and revenue. However, there might be movies with extremely low budget anyway.

Duplicates¶

Are there any movies that are duplicates? If yes, is it a full duplicate (all column values are exactly the same) or a partial duplicate (some of the values are the same)? In the latter case, it might not be a duplicate at all, but just a different movie.

Next, we will check if there are any full duplicates and if there are any partial duplicates, i.e. any movies with the same title and release year. We could select another features, but the title and release year are available for all of the movies, and they could be considered as a unique identifier for each movie. However, we will check also duplicates in terms of the movie id, which is a unique identifier for each movie.

Data Cleaning¶

The data cleaning steps include:

  • Remove unnecessary columns
  • Drop duplicates
  • Remove missing values
  • Remove low-budget movies (budget_adj less than 100,000 dollars) and prepare the final datasets for analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

We will explore data to find answers to following questions:

  1. Is there correlation between budget and revenue?
  2. Which genres are associated with high revenues?
  3. What is the optimal movie runtime with respect to revenue?
  4. Are movies with high revenues rated highly by users?

We will use all three prepared dataframes:

  • df_sub_100k - movies with budget_adj higher than or equal to 100,000 dollars
  • df_sub_high_bdg - high-budget movies with budget_adj above approximately 30 million dollars
  • df_sub_low_bdg - low-budget movies with budget_adj below approximately 30 million dollars

(Note: Again, the boundary of 30 million dollars is not an official boundary to distinguish high and low budget movies. It's just an arbitrary value used in this project.)

First, define plotting functions to make plotting easier.

Function to plot histograms¶

In [38]:
# Define function to plot a histogram
def plot_hist(x, number_of_bins, title, x_label, y_label):
    # Create plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.hist(x, bins=number_of_bins);
    
    # Adjust histogram appearance
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='x', style='plain')
    plt.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=12);

Function to plot scatter plots¶

In [39]:
# Define function to plot a scatter plot
def plot_scatter(x, y, title, x_label, y_label):
    # Create plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.scatter(x=x, y=y, alpha=0.3)
    
    # Adjust scatter plot appearance
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='both', style='plain')
    plt.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=12)
    plt.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=12)
    
    # Add regression line
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(x,y)
    plt.plot(x, slope*x+intercept, 'orange', alpha=0.7)
    
    # Print correlation coefficient
    print('Correlation coefficient for linear regression: {:.2f}\n'.format(r_value));

To calculate regression parameters, linregress function from scipy.stats module is used. We used the approach described in How to add regression line and regression line equation on graph.

Functions to plot bar charts¶

Simple bar chart with or without values above bars¶
In [40]:
# Define function to plot bar chart with/without values above bars
def plot_bar_simple(data, feature, labels, bar_width, title, x_label, y_label, x_label_rotation, dist):
    # Create bar chart
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    locations = np.arange(len(data))
    heights = feature
    labels = labels
    width = bar_width
    plt.bar(locations, heights, width)
    
    # Adjust bar chart appearance
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(locations, labels, rotation=x_label_rotation)
    plt.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=12)
    plt.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=10)
    
    # Add values to bars if parameter dist is greater than zero; if dist=0, values are not given
    if dist>0:
        for loc, height in enumerate(heights):
            plt.text(loc, height+dist, round(height), horizontalalignment='center', fontsize=10);
Combined bar chart with or without values above bars¶
In [41]:
# Define function to plot combined bar chart with/without values above bars

def plot_bar_combined(data, feature_1, feature_2, scale, labels, title, name_feature_1, name_feature_2, x_label, y_label, x_label_rotation, dist):
    # Create bar chart
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    locations = np.arange(len(data))
    # Use scale parameter to adjust values
    heights_r = feature_1/scale
    heights_b = feature_2/scale
    labels = labels
    width = 0.4
    plt.bar(locations-0.2, heights_r, width, label=name_feature_1);
    plt.bar(locations+0.2, heights_b, width, label=name_feature_2, color='orange')
    
    # Adjust bar chart appearance
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(locations, labels, rotation=x_label_rotation)
    plt.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=12)
    plt.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=12)
    plt.legend(fontsize=12);
    
    # Add values to bars if parameter dist is greater than zero; if dist=0, values are not given
    if dist>0:
        for loc, height in enumerate(heights_r):
            plt.text(loc-0.2, height+dist, round(height), horizontalalignment='center', fontsize=10)

        for loc, height in enumerate(heights_b):
            plt.text(loc+0.2, height+dist, round(height), horizontalalignment='center', fontsize=10);

Following resources have been used to create bar chart plotting functions:

  • Multiline xticks labels
  • Adding value labels on a matplotlib bar chart

# Define function to modify genres - remove '|' and make the genres appear in separate lines, and shorten 'Science Fiction' to 'Sci Fi'
def adjust_genres(genres):
    return genres.replace('|', '\n').replace('Science Fiction', 'Sci Fi')

Here we will try to find out which genres are the best ones when it comes to earnings. We will examine genres with the highest revenues, budgets and revenue-to-budget ratios.

It looks like adventure and action in combination with genres like horror, thriller, fantasy, science fiction or even family are proper ingredients of a successful movie - they appear at almost all places in our top 10, except for the 5th place with family/animation/drama.

Conclusions¶

In this project, we have explored and analyzed the movie dataset. The analysis was built around four questions related to movie revenues, budgets, genres, ratings and runtimes, and these questions were approached by descriptive statistics.

Revenue vs. budget. Correlation between the revenue and budget is positive. That is, the higher the budget, the higher the revenue. However, the relationship is not uniform, and there are exceptions - movies with extremely high budgets and low revenues, or movies with extremely high revenues, but low budgets.

Revenue vs. genres. We have found out that some genres are more likely to generate higher revenues when comparing to others. Action, adventure, crime, drama, horror, thriller, family, fantasy and science fiction are all examples of genres that are beneficial from the revenue point of view. On the other hand, western or war movies are most likely the ones that would generate lower earnings.
We have also observed that high budget does not necessarily lead to high revenue. To investigate a little bit more, the revenue-to-budget ratios per movie genres were used to compare performance in the movie genres. In addition, the comparison was carried out with high-budget and low-budget movies separately. Here it was visible, that low-budget movies had on average higher revenue-to-budget ratios when comparing to high-budget movies. Although the best exact genres categories are completely different for the high- and low-budget movies, they bear similar characteristics - we could identify genres like adventure, drama on thriller in the both lists.

Revenue vs. runtime. Next, we looked on the correlation between revenue and runtime. There is quite a broad interval of runtimes, 125-250 minutes, that is characteristic for movies with the highest revenues. Because of this, runtime is probably not a very specific measure for the movie success.

Revenue vs. user rating. In the last part, the relation between the movie revenue and user ratings was explored. Generally, the better the rating, the higher the revenue. On the other side, poorly rated movies had also lower revenues.

Exploratory analysis revealed some interesting insights into the studied dataset. However, more sophisticated approach including inferential statistics and/or machine learning techniques would be necessary to gain better understanding of the data and draw final conclusions.
